<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
This species was initially described as a species of 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Araliaceae" genus="Aralia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aralia" order="Umbelliflorae" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Aralia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., then transferred to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Araliaceae" genus="Schefflera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Schefflera" order="Apiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Schefflera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
J.R. Forst. &amp; G. Forst. However, molecular studies (
<bibRefCitation author="Lowry II, PP" journalOrPublisher="Brittonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="42 - 61" refId="B6509213" refString="Lowry II, PP, Plunkett, GM, Frodin, DG, 2013. Revision of Plerandra A. Gray (Araliaceae). I. A synopsis of the genus with an expanded circumscription and a new infrageneric classification. Brittonia 65: 42 - 61" title="Revision of Plerandra A. Gray (Araliaceae). I. A synopsis of the genus with an expanded circumscription and a new infrageneric classification" volume="65" year="2013">Lowry II et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
) have demonstrated that 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Araliaceae" genus="Schefflera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Schefflera" order="Apiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Schefflera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the largest genus of the 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Araliaceae" genus="Schefflera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Apiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Araliaceae</taxonomicName>
family, is grossly polyphyletic. The species, belonging to the Melanesian clade, are preferably accommodated in a separate genus, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A.Gray" authorityYear="1854" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Araliaceae" genus="Plerandra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Plerandra" order="Apiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Plerandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
A. Gray. It counts 32 species that are restricted to Melanesia (Fiji, New Caledonia, New Guinea, the Solomon Islands and Vanuatu). A few species are commonly cultivated as ornamentals, especially 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. elegantissima" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegantissima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. elegantissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lowry, G. M. Plunkett &amp; Frodin" authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Veitch ex Mast." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Araliaceae" genus="Plerandra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Plerandra elegantissima" order="Apiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elegantissima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Plerandra elegantissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to New Caledonia, but widely cultivated for its decorative juvenile foliage that is palmately divided, formed by 7-12 almost linear leaflets with grossly and irregularly dentate margins. Like other species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Araliaceae" genus="Schefflera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Schefflera" order="Apiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Schefflera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s.l., fruits are drupaceous and thus consumed by berry-eating birds. As a result, ornamental species of this genus are easily dispersed; they are particularly frequent as epiphytes on palm trees, also in the Canary Islands, where 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Malacostraca" family="Mysidae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. actinophylla" order="Mysida" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="actinophylla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">S. actinophylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Endl.) Harms and 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Malacostraca" family="Mysidae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. arboricola" order="Mysida" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arboricola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">S. arboricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Hayata) Merr. are increasingly recorded (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Verloove, F" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="63 - 78" refId="B6510073" refString="Verloove, F, Reyes-Betancort, JA, 2011. Additions to the flora of Tenerife (Canary Islands, Spain). Collectanea Botanica 30: 63 - 78" title="Additions to the flora of Tenerife (Canary Islands, Spain)" volume="30" year="2011">Verloove and Reyes-Betancort 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Verloove, F" journalOrPublisher="Acta Botanica Croatica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="120 - 131" refId="B6509982" refString="Verloove, F, 2017. New xenophytes from the Canary Islands (Gran Canaria and Tenerife; Spain). Acta Botanica Croatica 76 (2): 120 - 131" title="New xenophytes from the Canary Islands (Gran Canaria and Tenerife; Spain)" volume="76" year="2017">Verloove 2017</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Otto, R" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509398" refString="Otto, R, Verloove, F, 2018. New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species - Part 2. Collectanea Botanica 37" title="New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species - Part 2" volume="37" year="2018">Otto and Verloove 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Up to now, 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. elegantissima" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elegantissima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">P. elegantissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had only been recorded from La Palma in the Canary Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Otto, R" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509388" refString="Otto, R, Verloove, F, 2016. New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species. Collectanea Botanica 35" title="New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species" volume="35" year="2016">Otto and Verloove 2016</bibRefCitation>
). It was observed to freely reproduce from seed in ornamental gardens and public greens. In Tenerife, it was seen in comparable circumstances in December 2019.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lowry, G. M. Plunkett &amp; Frodin" authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Veitch ex Mast." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Araliaceae" genus="Plerandra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Plerandra elegantissima" order="Apiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elegantissima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Plerandra elegantissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an emerging invasive weed in some parts of the world, for instance, in South Africa (several online references).
</paragraph>
